The BNP in the [[United Kingdom general election, 2001|2001 general election]] saved five deposits (out of 33 contested seats) and secured its best general election result in [[Oldham West and Royton]] (which had recently been the scene of racially motivated rioting between white and Asian youths) where party leader [[Nick Griffin]] secured 16% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/dec/12/politics.race1 |title=How the BNP turned racial hatred into votes |last=Ward |first=Lucy |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2001}}</ref>

The [[United Kingdom general election, 2005|2005 general election]] was considered a major breakthrough by the BNP, as they picked up 192,746 votes in the 119 constituencies it contested, took a 0.7% share of the overall vote, and retained a deposit in 40 of the seats.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4519347.stm |work=BBC News |title=BNP sees increase in total votes |date=6 May 2005 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

The BNP put forward candidates for 338 out of 650 seats for the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|2010 general election]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecst.org.uk/docs/Elections%20Report%20-%20General%20Elections%202010_for%20web.pdf |title=Elections Report |publisher=Community Security Trust |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> gaining 563,743 votes<ref name="BBC National Results">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/ |work=BBC News |title=National Results |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> (1.9%), finishing in fifth place and failing to win any seats. However, a record of 73 deposits were saved. Party chairman Griffin came third in the [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]] constituency, behind [[Margaret Hodge]] of Labour and Simon Marcus of the Conservatives, who were first and second respectively. At 14.6%, this was the BNP's best result in any of the seats it contested that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/a11.stm |title=Barking |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

===Local elections===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#Local_elections|l1=British National Party election results (local elections)}}
The BNP's first electoral success came in 1993, when [[Derek Beackon]] was returned as a councillor in [[Millwall]], London. He lost his seat in elections the following year. The next BNP success in local elections was not until the [[Burnley Council election, 2002|2002]] local elections, when three BNP candidates gained seats on [[Burnley (borough)|Burnley]] council.<ref name="parliament.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snsg-05064.pdf |title=Electoral performance of the British National Party in the UK |date=15 May 2009 |work= |publisher=Parliament |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP's first councillor for six years was John Haycock, elected as a parish councillor for [[Bromyard and Winslow]] in [[Herefordshire]] in 2000. Haycock failed to attend any council meetings for six months and was later disqualified from office.{{sfn|Copsey|2008|pp=116–117}}

The party had 55 councillors for a time in 2009.<ref name="parliament.uk"/> After the [[United Kingdom local elections, 2013|2013 local county council elections]], the BNP was left with a total of two [[borough council]]lors in [[Local government in England|England]]:<ref>{{cite news |first=Conal |last=Urquhart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/may/04/bnp-members-breed-elections |title=BNP calls on members to breed more after elections disaster |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 2013 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}</ref>

As of 2011, the BNP had yet to make "a major breakthrough" on local councils.{{sfn|Bottom|Copus|2011|p=159}}
The BNP's councillors usually had "an extremely limited impact on local politics" because they were isolated as individuals or small groups on the council.{{sfn|Macklin|2011b|p=235}} Councillors from the main parties often disliked their BNP colleagues and deemed having to work alongside them as an affront to dignity and decency.{{sfn|Bottom|Copus|2011|p=152}}
Questions were often raised as to whether BNP councillors could adequately represent the interests of all of their local constituents.{{sfn|Bottom|Copus|2011|p=153}} On being elected, Beackon for instance stated that he refused to serve his Asian constituents in Millwall.{{sfn|Bottom|Copus|2011|p=154}} There were also allegations made that BNP councillors had particularly low attendance at council meetings, although research indicated that this was not the case, with the BNP's attendance record being largely average.{{sfn|Bottom|Copus|2011|p=148}}

There is evidence to suggest that racially and religiously motivated crime increased in those areas where BNP councillors had been elected.{{sfnm|1a1=Copsey|1y=2008|1p=198|2a1=Macklin|2y=2011b|2p=235}} For instance, after the 1993 election of Beackon, there was a spike in racist attacks in the borough of Tower Hamlets.{{sfn|Macklin|2011b|pp=26–27}} BNP members were directly responsible for some of this; the party's national organiser [[Richard Edmonds]] was sentenced to three months imprisonment for his part in an attack on a black man and his white girlfriend.{{sfn|Macklin|2011b|pp=26–27}}

===Regional assemblies and parliaments===

{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#National_Assembly_for_Wales|l1=British National Party election results (National Assembly for Wales)|British_National_Party_election_results#Scottish_Parliament|l2=British National Party election results (Scottish Parliament)|British_National_Party_election_results#Northern_Ireland_Legislative_Assembly|l3=British National Party election results (Northern Ireland Legislative Assembly)}}

[[File:Richard Barnbrook BNP at mayoral election2.jpg|thumb|right|Barnbrook in 2008]]

BNP lead candidate [[Richard Barnbrook]] won a seat in the [[London Assembly]] in May 2008, after the party gained 5.3% of the London-wide vote.<ref name="Barn53">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7381633.stm |title=BNP wins seat in London Assembly |date=3 May 2008 |work=BBC News |accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> However, in August 2010, he resigned the party whip and became an independent.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |date=29 September 2010 |title=BNP expels Richard Barnbrook as bitter feud threatens to tear apart party |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/sep/29/bnp-barnbrook-expelled-griffin-feud |work=The Guardian |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>

In the 2007 [[Welsh Assembly]] [[National Assembly for Wales election, 2007|elections]], the BNP fielded 20 candidates, four in each of the five regional lists, with [[Nick Griffin]] standing in the [[South Wales West (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|South Wales West]] region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Immigration a key issue, says BNP |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/6558981.stm |work=BBC News |date=16 April 2007 |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> It did not win any seats, but was the only minor party to have saved deposits in the electoral regions, one in the North Wales region and the other in the South Wales West region. In total the BNP polled 42,197 votes (4.3%).

In the [[National Assembly for Wales election, 2011|2011 Welsh Assembly elections]], the BNP fielded 20 candidates, four in each of the five regional lists and for the first time 7 candidates were fielded in [[First-past-the-post voting|FPTP]] constituencies. On the regional lists, the BNP polled 22,610 votes (2.4%), down 1.9% from 2007.<ref name="BBC News: Wales elections">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/wales.stm |title=Wales elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref> In 2 out of the 7 FPTP constituencies contested the BNP saved deposits: ([[Swansea East (Assembly constituency)|Swansea East]] and [[Islwyn (Assembly constituency)|Islwyn]]).<ref name="BBC News: Wales elections"/>

In the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]], the party fielded 32 candidates, entitling it to public funding and an election broadcast, prompting criticism.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uaf.org.uk/2007/08/no-to-public-funds-for-fascism/ |title=No to public funds for fascism |accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> The BNP received 24,616 votes (1.2%), no seats were won, nor were any deposits saved.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} In the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election]], the BNP fielded 32 candidates in the regional lists. 15,580 votes were polled (0.78%).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/region/html/scotland.stm |title=Scotland elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref>

The BNP fielded 3 candidates for the first time in three constituencies each in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly election, 2011|2011 Northern Ireland Legislative Assembly elections]] ([[Belfast East (Assembly constituency)|Belfast East]], [[East Antrim (Assembly constituency)|East Antrim]] and [[South Antrim (Assembly constituency)|South Antrim]]). 1,252 votes were polled (0.2%), winning no seats for the party.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/northern_ireland.stm |title=Northern Ireland elections |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 April 2013}}</ref>

===European Parliament===
{{Main|British_National_Party_election_results#European_Parliament||l1=British National Party election results (European Parliament)}}
The BNP has taken part in European Parliament elections since 1999, when they received 1.13% of the total vote (102,647 votes).

In the [[European Parliament Election, 2004 (UK)|2004 elections to the European Parliament]], the BNP won 4.9% of the vote, making it the sixth biggest party overall, but did not win any seats.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk">{{cite news |last=Wheeler |first=Brian |title=Will BNP election gains last? |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4968406.stm |accessdate=12 April 2013 |work=BBC News |date=5 May 2006}}</ref>

The BNP won two seats in the European Parliament in the [[European Parliament election, 2009 (United Kingdom)|2009 elections]]. [[Andrew Brons]] was elected in the [[Yorkshire and the Humber (European Parliament constituency)|Yorkshire and the Humber]] regional constituency with 9.8% of the vote.<ref name="BBC-BNP first seat">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8088133.stm |title=Labour slumps to historic defeat |work=BBC News |date=8 June 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> Party chairman [[Nick Griffin]] was elected in the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West region]], with 8% of the vote.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/elections/euro/09/html/ukregion_34.stm |title=European Election 2009: North West |date=8 June 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=14 April 2013}}</ref> Nationally, the BNP received 6.26%.

The British Government announced in 2009 that the BNP's two MEPs would be denied some of the access and information afforded to other MEPs. The BNP would be subject to the "same general principles governing official impartiality" and they would receive "standard written briefings as appropriate from time to time", but diplomats would not be "proactive" in dealing with the BNP MEPs and that any requests for policy briefings from them would be treated differently and on a discretionary basis.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/09/diplomats-shun-nick-griffin-bnp-europe |title= UK diplomats shun BNP officials in Europe |accessdate=1 April 2013 |first=Ian |last=Traynor |date=9 July 2009 |work=The Guardian }}</ref>

